frameDefinitions: A flying Vehicle comes to the ground at a Goal in a controlled fashion, typically (but not necessarily) operated by an operator.
While in motion, an Impactor makes sudden, forcible contact with the Impactee, or two Impactors both move, mutually making forcible contact.
An Assailant physically attacks a Victim (which is usually but not always sentient), causing or intending to cause the Victim physical damage.
In this frame a Theme moves in a certain Direction which is often determined by gravity or other natural, physical forces.
An Agent disables a flying or floating Patient, causing it to be unable to support itself in its current medium.
frameExamples: A police helicopter <t>landed</t> just outside my neighborhood at around midnight last night.
The massive metal foot <t>hit</t> the ground with a huge thud.
As soon as he stepped out of the bar he was <t>set</t> upon by four men in ski-masks.
It's rumored that she <t>downed</t> a helicopter with a precisely fired arrow.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Vehicle</fen> comes to the ground, usually (but not necessarily) under the control of an operator.
<fen>Goal</fen> is any expression that tells where the <fen>Vehicle</fen> ends up, or would end up, as a result of the motion.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the aircraft lands.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the landing occurs.
The entity that hits the <fen>Impactee</fen>.
The entity which is hit by the <fen>Impactor</fen>.
The multiple entities that collide.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
This role is the being or entity that is injured by the <fen>Assailant</fen>'s attack.
The person (or other self-directed entity) that is attempting physical harm to the <fen>Victim</fen>.
This role identifies the time when the <fen>Assailant</fen> attacks the <fen>Victim</fen>.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Assailant</fen> makes an assault on the <fen>Victim</fen>.
This role identifies the general <fen>Area</fen> in which motion takes place when the motion is understood to be irregular or not to consist of a single, linear path.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is the location the <fen>Theme</fen> ends up in (often unintentionally).
<fen>Path</fen> refers to (a part of) the ground over which the <fen>Theme</fen> travels  or to a landmark past which the <fen>Theme</fen> travels.
The <fen>Theme</fen> is the entity that changes location.
The <fen>Source</fen> is the location the <fen>Theme</fen> occupies before the Motion occurs.
The direction of motion of the <fen>Theme</fen>.  <fen>Direction</fen> characterizes the <fen>Path</fen> of motion according to some system of orientation, most often that imposed by gravity.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the Motion occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where motion specified by <fen>Source</fen>, <fen>Path</fen> or <fen>Goal</fen> occurs.
The <fen>Agent</fen> forces the <fen>Patient</fen> to come to the ground.
The <fen>Patient</fen> is the entity that is being forced to the ground.
An event which causes the <fen>Patient</fen> to come to the ground.
The time at which the event takes place.
The location at which the event takes place.
